        <td valign="top"><p class="instruct_normal"><img src="images/title_faq.gif" alt="Frequently Asked Questions" height="50" width="380" border="0"></p> <p class="grownups_bold_red"><font color="#ed1c24">Q. Why is Caillou bald?</font></p> <p class="instruct_normal">A. His character design is based upon the much younger literary property that existed prior to the animation series. Generally, for children, Caillou is a larger than life image of a preschooler. They don’t care about the hair issue. Not only do they not bring it up, but when asked to focus on it specifically in research groups, they laughed and replied that “he just doesn’t have any”.</p> <p class="grownups_bold_red"><font color="#ed1c24">Q. What is the educational rationale for the series?</font></p> <p class="instruct_normal">A. Both CINAR and PBS have long been champions of high-quality, non-violent, pro-social television programming for children. Based on research by acclaimed child psychologist Nicole Nadeau, the CAILLOU stories help children grow with self-esteem, confidence and independence.</p> <p class="grownups_bold_red"><font color="#ed1c24">Q. How is CAILLOU different from other pre-school series?</font></p> <p class="instruct_normal">A. Most television animation is usually used to take you where you can’t really go. What sets CAILLOU apart is that there is a reversal in how reality and fantasy are portrayed. The animated world is very realistic, which is very unusual for preschool programs. Children see Caillou as a “real” little boy to whom they can easily relate. Caillou’s adventures portray the relationship between small children and the world around them. Each story addresses real problems, conflicts and joys typical of a young child’s development. Children see themselves in Caillou, which strengthens the bond they share with their young hero. Caillou’s vocabulary is that of a 4 year-old. Caillou talks like real kids talk -- not how adults think children talk. The simplicity of the animation and the bright colors are extremely appealing, and the warmth and wit of the puppets complete the experience -- making it one filled with delight.</p> <p class="grownups_bold_red"><font color="#ed1c24">Q. How did the CAILLOU television series start?</font></p> <p class="instruct_normal">A. Since 1987 Caillou books from Les Editions Chouette have sold more than two million copies worldwide and have been translated into French, Spanish and other languages. CINAR actively pursued the book property with the goal of developing it into an animated series. Short animated episodes of CAILLOU premiered in 1997 in Canada. The overwhelming success of the animated series led to the partnership of CINAR and PBS to produce the half-hour CAILLOU series for public television, and subsequently additional books based on the television series.</p></td>
